# AGENTS.md — {{PROJECT_NAME}} brain

This repository is the **{{PROJECT_NAME}} brain**: the autonomy and governance
layer for the project, instantiated from Brain Factory. It coordinates the
project's app repos and keeps decisions, continuity, and quality durable in
GitHub. This file follows the cross-tool [AGENTS.md](https://agents.md) standard,
so any coding agent can work here.

## What this repo is (and is not)

- **Is:** the brain — operating contract, continuity log, decision records,
  capabilities map, and the `{{CMD_PREFIX}}-*` command set.
- **Is not:** the application code. App code lives in the repos listed under
  `app_repos` in `brain.manifest.json`; the brain coordinates them.

## Operating contract (read first)

`00-governance/OPERATING-CONTRACT.md` is authoritative. Non-negotiables:

- GitHub artifacts (issues, PRs, ADRs) are the system of record — not chat memory.
- Keep work bounded: one objective per PR, with acceptance criteria and validation.
- Run the open/close session ritual; continuity is written back every session.

## Commands

Commands are invoked as `{{CMD_PREFIX}}-<base>`. Each ships as both a Claude Code
skill and a GitHub Copilot prompt, so it runs under whichever agent you use:

- `{{CMD_PREFIX}}-status` — read-only state of backlog, PRs, CI, and brain health.
- `{{CMD_PREFIX}}-continue` — take the top backlog item through to a pull request.
- `{{CMD_PREFIX}}-sync` — run the close ritual (continuity writeback, capabilities refresh, push).
- `{{CMD_PREFIX}}-review` — pre-merge review of a branch or PR.

See `03-templates/agent-commands/` for the full set and `01-docs/CAPABILITIES.md`
for the generated capability map.

## Runtime-agnostic by design

This brain is not tied to any single AI vendor. The `agent_runtimes` field in
`brain.manifest.json` declares which runtimes are supported, and **`none` is
always supported**: the deterministic ops tasks (via the Brain Factory adapter
seam) run with no LLM at all. Paid or enterprise runtimes are additive and never
required to operate the brain.

## Conventions and boundaries

- Numbered structure (`00-governance` … `08-ops`) — keep files in their lane.
- **Core vs extensions:** anything under a `core/` namespace is hub-owned and
  upgraded by `{{CMD_PREFIX}}-upgrade` — do not hand-edit it. Project-specific
  work goes under `extensions/`, declared in `brain.manifest.json`.
- Markdown is the default; keep diagrams in `01-docs/diagrams/`.

## Safety

- Make changes through pull requests; do not push directly to the default branch.
- Never commit secrets. Report vulnerabilities privately, not in public issues.

## Permanent framework operating standards

### SYNC-LATEST-FIRST STANDARD (required)

- Before starting work in this brain or its app repos, sync to the latest online
  default branch first (`git fetch`; base on `origin/<default>`).
- Start each new work session from an up-to-date default branch.
- Re-sync lane/app repositories before touching them.
- Before merge, verify the PR is mergeable against current online default branch.
- On session start/rehydration, refresh managed lanes before reporting or acting.

### CLEANUP-NO-STALE-STATE STANDARD (required)

- Cleanup triad: remote **BRANCH**, local **WORKTREE**, owning **SESSION**.
- Tear down the full triad together after merge.
- Session definition by toolchain:
  - GitHub Copilot: the app/project session and its worktree.
  - Claude Code: the conversation/session workspace.
- Apply a no-loss gate before deleting any triad element (branch/worktree/session):
  preserve/escalate if unique unmerged content exists.
- Run periodic stale-state audits and flag merged-but-undeleted branches,
  branches with no open PR, orphaned worktrees, and orphaned sessions.
- Target one active worktree and one active session per active task.

### CONTINUITY-CAPTURE / BRAIN-MEMORY WRITEBACK STANDARD (required)

- For work executed in lane repositories (product/runtime or governance), write
  brain continuity entries that capture WHAT, WHY, WHERE (repo + PR/commit), and
  OUTCOME.
- Orchestrator-directed or orchestrator-executed work must be written back to
  the continuity ledger and master session index.
- A lane change with no brain continuity entry is a defect (memory loss).
- Capture timing: in-progress entry at work start / PR open, then finalize on
  merge with outcome.
- Cross-reference product/runtime PRs and brain continuity entries in both
  directions where practical.
- No-loss continuity invariant: brain memory covers all lane repos, not only
  governance.
